# MCP \- ABAC Policy Demo Setup Instructions

| Date | Author | Comments |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| Nov 5, 2025 | Vishwas Nallabelli | Initial Version based on Maximise session on Nov  |

## **Introduction**

Customers are quite excited about rolling out MCP and A2A features to their customers and internal employees. MuleSoft MCP servers enable you to expose tools to both internal and external organizations. While it is a very powerful feature, security is of prime importance. We are faced with questions such as

1. How do we secure MCP tools and track their use ?  
2. How do we expose tools based on user profile? Ex: Read only MCP Tools to a certain group of users and All tools to admins  
3. How do we roll out the MCP tools in a large enterprise ? 

## **Solution:**

MuleSoft Flex Gateway is built with MCP Policies that can secure your MCP Servers while being able to verify the identity of the user based on the profile set in your Identity Provider(Okta, Azure etc). The following sections will help you set up an end to end demo. 

1. [**Setup Okta**](#setup-okta)  
2. [**Configure Flex Gateway and Open ID Connect as client provider in Anypoint.**](#configure-flex-gateway-and-open-id-connect-as-client-provider-in-anypoint.)  
3. [**Apply Policies on MCP Server**](#3.-applying-mcp-policies)  
4. [**Testing ABAC Policy**](#4.-testing-abac-policy)  
 


   ## 

1. ## Setup Okta {#setup-okta}

   

| Sign up Okta at [www.okta.com/free-trial](http://www.okta.com/free-trial).  *Do not sign up for the developer account as it will not have all the features needed for this demo*       After you login with credentials, click on Admin in Okta | ![][image1] |
| :---- | :---- |
| **Add groups as Scope:** Setup \-\> Security \-\> API-\> Click on hyperlink default \-\> Navigate to Scopes Tab \-\> Add Scope   **SetUp Claims**:  Setup \-\> Security \-\> API-\> Click on hyperlink default \-\> Navigate to Claims Tab \-\> Add Claim-\>  Fill Values as shown in Screenshot  | ![][image2]  ![][image3] |
| **Access Policy:** In the same screen go to tab Access Policies and click Add New Access Policy.   | ![][image4] |
| **Access Rule**: While inside the new Access policy click on Add New Rule | ![][image5] |
| **Add People:** Navigate to Directory \-\> People and add 3 People with access to their email addresses as Okta sends verification to those emails and we need at least 2 active emails to show in demo.  | ![][image6] |
| **Add Groups:** Navigate to Directory \-\> Groups and add 2 groups with names MCP\_Basic and MCP\_Admins.  Add 2 users that you created under the MCP\_Admins group and 1 user under the MCP\_Basic group using the Assign People button under each group.  | ![][image7] |
| **Create Application:** Now we will create an Application which is referenced by Client ID and Secret. The invoking MCP Client application (Ex: ChatGPT, Slack, Claude) will be assigned with credentials. This will be used for the OAuth authentication step.  Admin Console \-\> Applications \-\> Applications \-\> Create App Integration In the pop up screen select API Services Give a Name \- Ex:ABACDemoApp Store the Client ID and Client Secret Leave the configuration as is for this demo | ![][image8] ![][image9] |
| **8\. IDP Token for Anypoint: Generate Token to access Okta Authorization Server. This is essential in the next step when setting up IDP in Anypoint platform. Navigate to Security-\>API-\> Tokens tab Store the generate token securely.**  | ![][image10] ![][image11] ![][image12] |

   

   

   

2. ## Configure Flex Gateway and Open ID Connect as client provider in Anypoint. {#configure-flex-gateway-and-open-id-connect-as-client-provider-in-anypoint.}

| Managed Flex Gateway Config: Ensure the organization you are using to demo is enabled with Managed Flex Gateway. If already enabled and you have a Managed Flex Gateway instance ready then you can skip this step. If you don’t have a Managed Flex Gateway ready then ensure you follow the steps to set up one.  | [https://docs.mulesoft.com/gateway/latest/flex-gateway-managed-set-up](https://docs.mulesoft.com/gateway/latest/flex-gateway-managed-set-up)  |
| :---- | :---- |
| **Get OAuth Server Details:** Navigate to Okta Admin Screen \-\> Admin Console \-\> API \-\> Click on default authorization server and click the MetaData URI. You will need details from this page to configure the IDP in Anypoint Platform.   |  ![][image13] **Default Server: ** ![][image14] Sample Oauth-authorization-server File:  ![][image15] |
| **10\. Configure IDP Provider in Anypoint Platform:** In MuleSoft Anypoint Platform click on Access Management \-\> Client Providers \-\> Add Client Provider. Authorization Header: “SSWS **\<\<Token from step IDP Token for Anypoint\>\>”** |   ![][image16] ![][image17] |
| **9\. Deploy your MCP Sample App.**  Import the attached Mule project into Anypoint Studio or ACB. Most of the MCP end points give stub responses in this example app. A few will work if the credentials are updated in configuration.yaml file. When deploying you can deploy to the same private space in which your Flex Gateway is deployed.  After deployment ensure you have a public endpoint setup from Application Runtime Manager-\> Application \-\> Ingress \-\> \+ Add Endpoint (External).  Store this URL in a text editor. | [https://drive.google.com/file/d/1StCNlP5sqrxLKKnNo8KywOhD2DI0rJbn/view?usp=drive\_link](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1StCNlP5sqrxLKKnNo8KywOhD2DI0rJbn/view?usp=drive_link)  **Ingress Config: ![][image18]** |

## 3\. Applying MCP Policies {#3.-applying-mcp-policies}

| MCP Management: In Anypoint Platform navigate to API manager-\> Agent and Tool instances \-\> Add MCP Server Select the Managed Flex Gateway created above and click Next Select Register a new MCP Server. Provide an asset Name Ex: ABAC-MCPServer In the next screen give BasePath as /abacdemo, ensure Client Provider is selected as Okta instance selected for this Environment.   Configure Upstream URL with the App URL deployed. You dont need to specify MCP endpoint, just the base APP URL Ex: https://hr-mcp-18decd.abcde88.usa-e2.cloudhub.io  | Add or Use Existing Managed Flex Gateway: ![][image19] Register New MCP Server: ![][image20] Downstream ![][image21] Upstream: ![][image22] |
| :---- | :---- |
| 2\.  Open Policies and add MCP Support as the first policy under the MCP Server we created (ABAC-MCPServer). Add JWT Validation:  Select JWT Key Origin as JWKS. Then type in the keys URL under JWKS  Url from the OAuth Server details from Okta Ex: [https://trial-7127384.okta.com/oauth2/default/v1/keys](https://trial-7127384.okta.com/oauth2/default/v1/keys) Add Message Logging Policy: Add 2 configurations. First one just indicating that Gateway has started to process via a string statement. Second one as \#\[authentication\] ideally we are printing the auth details when this is invoked.  | Policies: ![][image23] JWT Validation: ![][image24] Message Logging Policy: ![][image25] ![][image26] |
| 3\. ABAC Policy: We can now configure the ABAC Policy.  Add this Cedar Expression to allow only one Tool when MCP\_Basic users login.  *permit(principal, action \== Action::"tools/call", resource==Tool::"get-current-address") when {principal.properties.claims.Groups.contains("MCP\_Basic") };* Add this Cedar Expression to allow only one Tool when MCP\_Admin users login.  *permit(principal, action \== Action::"tools/call", resource)  when {    resource in \[Tool::"update-badge-reason", Tool::"get-user-profile", Tool::"generate-tracking-id", Tool::"create-date", Tool::"get-current-address", Tool::"create-jira-ticket", Tool::"check-tracking-status", Tool::"update-address", Tool::"create-salesforce-case", Tool::"get-badge-reason"\] &&   principal.properties.claims.Groups.contains("MCP\_Admins")};* | ![][image27] |

## 4\. Testing ABAC Policy {#4.-testing-abac-policy}

| Create Client App: Login to Anypoint Exchange. Navigate to Exchange-\> MCP Server \-\> Request Access Create an Application: Select the instance and click create new application  Select grant types authorized code Grant and client credential Grant Provide a redirect URI \- [http://localhost](http://localhost) Click create. Store the Client ID and Secret. We will use this for testing | ![][image28] |
| :---- | :---- |
| **Assign Groups to Application Created:** Now that the Application is created you can navigate to Okta under Applications. Click on the application and click on Assignments \-\> Groups and Click on Assign. Add the MCP\_Admin and MCP\_Basic Group  **Postman Steps:** When you demonstrate this you need to perform these steps to show MCP Tools that are visible for MCP Admin and MCP Basic.  This can be done directly from Postman using Auth Type OAuth 2.0 Fill in the details based on the OAuth Server details for the Auth URL and Token URL Callback URL should be the same as the one given when you requested access in Exchange. “[http://localhost](http://localhost)” Client ID and Client Secret will be the one “Credentials for Client App from Exchange” Scope should be profile groups openid After you configure all these click on Get new Access token. This will open a new browser window  Complete the Okta authentication screens using Admin account and this will show how the tokens are being used. Click on Use token.  Now you have received the token and you can test the MCP End point. You will see all the MCP Tools listed.  Click on clear cookies and repeat the steps but login with the user under MPC\_Basic group in Okta. Now you should see only tools allowed in the ABAC Policy.  | ![][image29] ![][image30]  ![][image31] ![][image32]  ![][image33]  ![][image34]![][image35] ![][image36]![][image37] |
